As the life expectancy of people living with HIV (PLWH) approaches that of the 
general population, the burden of comorbidities such as cardiovascular disease 
(CVD) is increasing. Regardless of HIV status, about 50% of CVD deaths worldwide 
occur in Asia, and Asian PLWH have a high prevalence of conventional CVD risk 
factors, such as smoking, dyslipidaemia, hypertension and insulin resistance or 
diabetes. As well as conventional CVD risk factors, PLWH have HIV-specific risk 
factors such as chronic inflammation, immune activation and endothelial damage, 
as well as risk factors related to antiretroviral therapy. This review describes 
the current knowledge on the epidemiology and risk factors of CVD in Asian PLWH 
and provides an Asian perspective on the recommendations for managing CVD risk 
in PLWH.

